<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="151" type="body length excluding head">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Body length excluding head.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Average male, 6.75 mm; average female, 6.5 mm.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="151">
<emphasis bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Body color</emphasis>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Heteropteron hasegawai Dabek &amp; Whitfield A dorsal habitus B lateral habitus." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.77.50577.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/425798" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">6</figureCitation>
): Mesosoma pale except propleuron dark. Head black, metasoma terga 1-5 pale, 6-8 dark with tergum 5 variable with dark patch medially distinctly triangular or with dusky patch, rarely absent. Antenna color: scape, pedicel, and flagellum dark. Coxa dark, trochanter mostly dark with posterior trochanter small light patch. Medial femur dark (8/13), lacking dark patch (5/13). Tarsus, aroliar pad ventrally white and dorsally black (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Heteropteron hasegawai Dabek &amp; Whitfield A lateral view of mesosoma B lateral view of hypopygium tip and ovipositor with sheaths C tibial spines D last tarsal segment, showing pectinate claws and whitish arolium." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.77.50577.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/425800" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">8D</figureCitation>
). Tarsal claw dark. Wings yellow and alternately banded light and dark (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Heteropteron hasegawai Dabek &amp; Whitfield A dorsal habitus B lateral habitus." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.77.50577.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/425798" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">6</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Heteropteron hasegawai Dabek &amp; Whitfield A frontal view of face B dorsal view of frons and ocelli, showing y-shaped ridge C wings, showing banding pattern." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.77.50577.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/425799" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">7C</figureCitation>
)).
</paragraph>
<caption doi="10.3897/jhr.77.50577.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/425798" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" start="Figure 6" startId="F6">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="151">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Figure 6.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dabek &amp; Whitfield" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Heteropteron" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Heteropteron hasegawai" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hasegawai">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Heteropteron hasegawai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Dabek &amp; Whitfield 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">A</emphasis>
dorsal habitus 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">B</emphasis>
lateral habitus.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="151">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Head</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Epistomal sulcus present, very light impression. Setose except vertex and occiput, sparse on clypeus. Setae light yellowish in color. Clypeus weakly and evenly convex. Margin truncate. Clypeus 2.2 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
broader than high, 2.4 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
length of malar space. Scape 2 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than broad, inner side deeply excised apically, base 1.7 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
narrower than broadest point. First flagellomere 2.6 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as broad.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="151">
<taxonomicName genus="Face" lsidName="Face" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Face</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Heteropteron hasegawai Dabek &amp; Whitfield A frontal view of face B dorsal view of frons and ocelli, showing y-shaped ridge C wings, showing banding pattern." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.77.50577.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/425799" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">7A</figureCitation>
) 1.8 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
broader than high. Galea dark, 1.2 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
wider than long. Anterior tentorial pits very distinct, deep. Glossae light, bilobed. Frons smooth, deeply excavated, excavation extending longitudinally from base of antennae to vertex and transversely from inner margin of left eye to inner margin or right eye. Frons dorsally with distinct Y-shaped ridge with branches terminating immediately anterior to median ocellus (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Heteropteron hasegawai Dabek &amp; Whitfield A frontal view of face B dorsal view of frons and ocelli, showing y-shaped ridge C wings, showing banding pattern." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.77.50577.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/425799" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">7B</figureCitation>
). Ocelli elevated within excavation with some setae between. Visible ridge at antennal base. Antenna with 34-36 flagellomeres.
</paragraph>
<caption doi="10.3897/jhr.77.50577.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/425799" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" start="Figure 7" startId="F7">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="151">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Figure 7.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dabek &amp; Whitfield" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Heteropteron" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Heteropteron hasegawai" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hasegawai">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Heteropteron hasegawai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Dabek &amp; Whitfield 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">A</emphasis>
frontal view of face 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">B</emphasis>
dorsal view of frons and ocelli, showing y-shaped ridge 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">C</emphasis>
wings, showing banding pattern.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="151">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Mesosoma</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Pronotum unsculptured except weakly on marginal ridges anteriorly and posteriorly, long light yellow setae anterodorsally. Pronotum light in color laterally and posterodorsally, dark anteriorly and ventrally. Notauli smooth, incomplete, distinct anteriorly, evanescent posteriorly, extending about half length of mesoscutum; mesoscutum smooth, 1.1 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
wider than long, flattened dorsally in lateral view, sparsely covered with yellow setae. Scutellum triangular, smooth, flat in lateral view, lateral areas of scutellum bare and smooth. Posterior end of scutellum lacking ridge at margin (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Heteropteron hasegawai Dabek &amp; Whitfield A dorsal habitus B lateral habitus." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.77.50577.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/425798" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">6A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="151">
<emphasis bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Propodeum smooth</emphasis>
, virtually without areola but with complete longitudinal furrow; pilosity abundant in vicinity of spiracles. Setae 6 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer then distance between each setae; spiracles 1.4 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than wide.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="151">
<taxonomicName genus="Subalar" lsidName="Subalar" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Subalar</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
depression smooth with median carina forming obtuse angle. 
<taxonomicName genus="Subalar" lsidName="Subalar" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" rank="genus">Subalar</taxonomicName>
prominence tapering posteriorly to pleural sulcus, smooth, convex. Pleural sulcus with double groove. Posterior margin of mesopleuron smooth, moderately setose ventrally with visible setal pits. Mesopleuron smooth (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Heteropteron hasegawai Dabek &amp; Whitfield A lateral view of mesosoma B lateral view of hypopygium tip and ovipositor with sheaths C tibial spines D last tarsal segment, showing pectinate claws and whitish arolium." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.77.50577.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/425800" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">8A</figureCitation>
). Metapleuron with distinct dorsal-ventral groove starting halfway down the dorsal edge of the metapleuron and ending at the posterior end, moderately setose, setae light in color.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="151">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Legs</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Hind tibia slightly broadening distally, distal end 1.8 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as proximal end. Hind femur 2.6 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as broad distally, distal end 2.1 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as proximal end. Hind basitarsus 1.2 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
the length of tarsomeres 2-5 combined, inner spur of hind tibia half the length of basitarsus. Second tarsus of fore leg 1.4 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than broad, fifth tarsus of foreleg 1.7 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than broad; second tarsus of mid leg 1.3 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than broad, fifth tarsus of mid leg 1.3 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than broad; second tarsus of hind leg 1.7 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than broad, fifth tarsus of hind leg 1.3 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than broad. Tibial spines, generally &lt;7, variable in number and pattern (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Heteropteron hasegawai Dabek &amp; Whitfield A lateral view of mesosoma B lateral view of hypopygium tip and ovipositor with sheaths C tibial spines D last tarsal segment, showing pectinate claws and whitish arolium." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.77.50577.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/425800" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">8C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="151">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Forewing</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
1.15 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than body. Pterostigma elongate, issuing 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">r</emphasis>
from its middle. Second submarginal cell long. Banding pattern as in Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Heteropteron hasegawai Dabek &amp; Whitfield A frontal view of face B dorsal view of frons and ocelli, showing y-shaped ridge C wings, showing banding pattern." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.77.50577.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/425799" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">7C</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="151">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Metasoma</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
First tergite 1.4 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
broader posteriorly than long. Third tergite 1.4 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as second tergite. All tergites polished. Second latero-tergite visible in dorsal view (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Heteropteron hasegawai Dabek &amp; Whitfield A dorsal habitus B lateral habitus." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.77.50577.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/425798" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">6A</figureCitation>
). Hypopygium broad, laterally truncate and rounded at tip (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Heteropteron hasegawai Dabek &amp; Whitfield A lateral view of mesosoma B lateral view of hypopygium tip and ovipositor with sheaths C tibial spines D last tarsal segment, showing pectinate claws and whitish arolium." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.77.50577.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/425800" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">8B</figureCitation>
), irregular blackened spot near tip. Ovipositor sheath as long as mesosoma with white streak at ventral base (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Heteropteron hasegawai Dabek &amp; Whitfield A lateral view of mesosoma B lateral view of hypopygium tip and ovipositor with sheaths C tibial spines D last tarsal segment, showing pectinate claws and whitish arolium." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.77.50577.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/425800" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">8B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
